\begin_layout Definition
If an individual chooses A out of a set of options including B, they should
 never choose B when faced with a choice of a different set of options which
 also includes A and B.
 More formally, if A is ever chosen when B is available, then there can
 be no set containing both alternatives from which B is chosen and A is
 not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, it must be the case that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given two distinct price vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}\neq\vec{p}'$
\end_inset

 and wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w\neq w'$
\end_inset

, the Walrasian demand functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(\vec{p},w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies WARP if the following holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}\cdot\vec{x}(\vec{p}',w')\leq w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(\vec{p},w)\neq\vec{x}(\vec{p}',w)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}'\cdot\vec{x}(\vec{p},w)>w'$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using Chris' notation from class, we can rewrite as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,q,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p,q,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies WARP if the following holds 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\left[p,q,w\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
