\begin_layout Subsection
Rationality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take the preference relationships (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that they are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
complete
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{x},\vec{y}\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}\succeq\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 (or both).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
transitive
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{x},\vec{y},\vec{z}\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that transitivity is a fairly strong assumption to make and for those
 of you interested in political economy or social welfare, you'll start
 thinking about ways to weaken this assumption.
 To the preference relationships we established in the manner above, we
 add further assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Desirability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the preferences we established above are such that larger
 amounts of goods are preferred to smaller amounts.
 We capture this assumption using one of the following three concepts (note
 that the mathematical definitions use commodity bundles consisting of two
 goods):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
(weak) monotonicity
\series default
: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\gg\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]\gg\left[{y_{1}\atop y_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

, implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succ\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
strong monotonicity
\series default
: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\geq\geq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]\geq\geq\left[{y_{1}\atop y_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I know that this is a really bad abuse of notation.
 A better way to write it would be if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq y_{i},\,\forall i$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}>y_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succ\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\neq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succ\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
local non-satiation
\series default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Think of this as a weaker form of monotonicity
\end_layout

\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{x}\in X$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\vec{y}\in X$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $||\vec{x}-\vec{y}||\leq\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}\succ\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you're not familiar with the concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

norms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 || .
 ||---think of it as the distance between two vectors in the Euclidean space.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if preferences are strongly monotone, then it is monotone; and
 that if preferences are monotone, then it is locally non-satiated.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Try Exercise 3.B.1 in MWG using the two good case.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convexity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also assume that the preferences over the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are convex.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall our discussion of convex sets and convex functions.
 This is now a new definition which is related to our discussion on the
 convexity of sets.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What does this mean? It means that the preferences that we are dealing
 with follow the rule of 
\shape italic
diminishing marginal rates of substitution
\shape default
.
 Furthermore, convexity of preferences can be viewed as economic agents'
 preference for diversification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically, convexity of preferences can be written as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{x},\vec{y},\vec{z}\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\vec{x}+(1-\alpha)\vec{y}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, there is another concept (which you will see below in the context
 of Leontief and linear preferences) that you may want to familiarize yourself
 with: preferences are 
\shape italic
strictly
\shape default
 convex if: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{x},\vec{y},\vec{z}\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}\succeq\vec{z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\vec{x}+(1-\alpha)\vec{y}\succ\vec{z}$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Compare Figures 3.B.3 and 3.B.4 in MWG to see the intuition behind the mathematical
 definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Continuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does continuity mean? As Chris stated in class, the continuity assumption
 rules out 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the preferences of the agent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Mathematically, preferences on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are continuous if for any sequence of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vec{x}_{n},\vec{y}_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{n}\succeq\vec{y}_{n}\forall n,$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\vec{x}_{n}=\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\vec{y}_{n}=\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do we care? See Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Preferences-and-utility"

\end_inset

 below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's review the continuity restriction on preferences by looking at a preferenc
e relationship that is not continuous---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 the Lexicographic preference relationship.
 The Lexicographic preference relationship is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succeq\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>y_{1}$
\end_inset

 or if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\geq y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The first commodity determines the preference relationship for all bundles
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq y_{1}$
\end_inset

, but where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

, the second commodity determines the preference relationship.
 If the first and second commodities are the same, then the third commodity
 determines the preference relationship, and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider a two commodity world where the sequence of bundles 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{n}=\left[{\frac{1}{n}\atop 0}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}=\left[{0\atop 1}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, for every single 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{n}\succ\vec{y}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 However, note that at the limits, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\vec{x}_{n}=\left[{0\atop 0}\right]\prec\left[{0\atop 1}\right]=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\vec{y}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In short, the preference relationship is not preserved at the limit points
 and therefore, Lexicographic preferences are not continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preferences and utility functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Preferences-and-utility"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do we care about all of the assumptions that we place on preferences?
 We care because we want to translate these preference relationships into
 mathematically tractable functions (or utility functions).
 Each of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

[r]estrictions on preferences translate into restrictions on the form of
 utility functions.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
MWG p.49.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let's look at each of the assumptions above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
Desirability
\shape default
: If we assume that an agent's preferences are monotonic (and so locally
 non-satiated), then we know that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\gg\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]\gg\left[{y_{1}\atop y_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\succ\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, or in terms of mathematically tractable utility functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})>u(\vec{y}).$
\end_inset

This means that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing function.
 Furthermore, if preferences are strongly monotone, this implies that preference
s are monotone 
\shape italic
and
\shape default
 locally non-satiated.
 If preferences are locally non-satiated, indifference curves are not thick.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
Convexity
\shape default
: If we assume that an agent's preferences are convex, then we know that
 the utility function representing these preferences must be quasiconcave.
 Review the math review notes and see why convexity of preferences translates
 into quasiconcave functions (HINT: Has to do with upper level sets).
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see this, we need to know another definition of quasiconcavity, which
 Chris discussed in class; namely that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is quasiconcave iff 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha\vec{x}+(1-\alpha)\vec{y})\geq min\{f(\vec{x}),f(\vec{y})\}.$
\end_inset

 For those interested, see Section 21.3 of Simon and Blume (1994) and MWG
 (pp.49-50).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Remember what we liked about quasiconcave utility functions from the math
 review?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
Continuity
\shape default
: We want the preference relationships we defined above to be continuous
 because this guarantees the existence of a continous utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 that represents these preferences.
 Why do we want continuous utility functions? It makes the math easier!
 We can 
\shape italic
usually
\shape default
 differentiate continuous utility functions.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An example of where continuity is satisfied but we are unable to use calculus
 is the Leontief preferences.
 Aside from continuity, a function must also be 
\shape italic
smooth
\shape default
 for it to be differentiable.
 In this class, we will assume that functions are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

, or twice differentiable.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Examples of utility functions and their two-dimensional representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before looking at a few examples, we need to remember a few things.
 In this class, we'll usually be dealing with two goods and functions with
 two variables that map these two variables onto the real line---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Because we are, in many instances, interested in the shape of these graphs,
 we might want to draw them on the three-dimensional Euclidean space.
 However, another way to represent these three dimensional graphs is to
 use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

level curves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

level sets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) on a two-dimensional space (which most of us are more accustomed to).
 Note that in the context of utility functions, these level curves are called
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

indifference curves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; when dealing with production functions, they may be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

isoquants
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; or when dealing with profit functions, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

iso-profit curves.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 They all mean the same thing! Now let's look at a few utility functions
 where the consumption space consists of two goods and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Leontief utility function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Leontief utility functions can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=\min\{ax_{1},bx_{2}\}.$
\end_inset

 The simplest form would set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, for an arbitrary level of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u},$
\end_inset

 the equation representing this indifference curve would be: 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\{x_{1},x_{2}\}=\bar{u}.$
\end_inset

 Let's draw the indifference curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Desirability assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Are Leontief preferences strongly monotone? No.
 What happens when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and you add 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 to only good 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

? 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=\min\{x_{1},x_{2}\}=\bar{u}=\min\{x_{1}+\epsilon,x_{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]\sim\left[{x_{1}+\epsilon\atop x_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
However, are Leontief preferences monotone? Yes, because it must be the
 case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\{x_{1}+\epsilon,x_{2}+\epsilon\}>\min\{x_{1},x_{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}+\epsilon\atop x_{2}+\epsilon}\right]\succ\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Are Leontief preferences convex? We could go through the mathematical steps
 (and in the instance of Lexicographic preferences, we have to), but let's
 consider a short cut.
 What is a consequence of convexity of preferences? Recall that it is the
 quasiconcavity of utility functions.
 What do quasiconcave utility functions have? Recall from math review that
 if a function is quasiconcave, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}^{+}$
\end_inset

, or the upper level set, is convex.
 Look at the indifference curves we drew and find the upper level set.
 Are preferences convex? Yes.
 Are they strictly convex? No.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we solve a utility maximization problem (hereinafter 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

UMP
