\begin_layout Subsection
Linear utility function (1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We can rewrite linear utility functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x_{1},x_{2})=\alpha x_{1}+\beta x_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta>0$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=ax_{1}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{\alpha}{\beta}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Do you remember why? Hint: it has to do with the ordinality of utility.
 Therefore, for a given level of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

, the equation representing this indifference curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $ax_{1}+x_{2}=\bar{u}\Rightarrow x_{2}=-ax_{1}+\bar{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's draw these indifference curves, but with a twist.
 Add a budget line where the price of good 1 and good 2 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

, respectively, and wealth is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 You'll need to consider two different cases.
 Can you see this?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Are the preferences represented by the linear utility function above strongly
 monotonic? Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1}+\epsilon,x_{2})=a(x_{1}+\epsilon)+x_{2}>ax_{1}+x_{2}=u(x_{1},x_{2}),$
\end_inset

 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[{x_{1}+\epsilon\atop x_{2}}\right]\succ\left[{x_{1}\atop x_{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, preferences which can be represented by linear utility functions
 of the form above are strongly monotonic.
 This means that linear utility functions represent preferences which are
 monotonic and locally non-satiated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Are preferences represented by linear utility functions convex? Again, instead
 of going through the math, let's look at the upper level sets using the
 graph we drew.
 Are preferences convex? Yes.
 Are they strictly convex? No.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we solve the UMP with linear utility, the optimizing agent will consume
 all in good 1 or all in good 2 depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $|-a|>|-\frac{p}{q}|$
\end_inset

or whether 
\begin_inset Formula $|-a|<|-\frac{p}{q}|$
\end_inset

.
 Does this make sense? Think in terms of the ratio of marginal utilities
 of consuming good 1 and good 2.
 If this doesn't seem clear to you, don't worry.
 We're going to go through it next week.
 
\end_layout

