Now let's look at an extension of the linear utility function we saw above
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=ax_{1}-x_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 We can write the equation for a given level of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $ax_{1}-x_{2}=\bar{u}\Rightarrow x_{2}=ax_{1}-\bar{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's draw these indifference curves with the same budget line as above.
 Note that the slope on the indifference curves is positive.
 
\end_layout

