\begin_layout Subsection
Quadratic utility function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When the functional form of the utility function is quadratic, it may take
 the following form: 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=-(x_{1}-a)^{2}-(x_{2}-b)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Trivially, for a given level of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

, the equation representing the indifference curve on the two-dimensional
 space is: 
\begin_inset Formula $-(x_{1}-a)^{2}-(x_{2}-b)^{2}=\bar{u}\Rightarrow(x_{1}-a)^{2}+(x_{2}-b)^{2}=-\bar{u}$
\end_inset

.
 The indifference curves for preferences represented by the above quadratic
 function will be concentric circles (the center of these circles being
 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

) and the level of utility depicted by the circles is decreasing as the
 radius of the circle increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Before considering the weak/strong monotonicity of preferences represented
 by a quadratic utility function of the form above, note that: 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\mathbb{R}^{2}\rightarrow0\cup\mathbb{R}^{-}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

