\begin_layout Subsection
Quasi-linear utility function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before going through the same exercises above, I'd like to point out that
 quasi-linear utility functions have certain attractive properties, which
 we will cover in the context of solving UMPs in the next section, such
 as additivity of utility with regards to the numeraire good and no wealth
 effects.
 Here is the definition of quasi-linear preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Preferences are quasi linear with regards to a certain good (usually good
 1, and usually referred to as the numeraire good) 1) if all indifference
 curves are parallel displacements of each other along the numeraire good's
 axis; and 2) if the numeraire is in fact a good.
 Quasi-linear preferences with regards to good 1 (or the numeraire) over
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 goods can be represented by a quasi-linear utility function of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})=ax_{1}+\phi(\vec{x}_{-1})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See also MWG Definition 3.B.7.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For ease of exposition, let's consider a specific quasi-linear utility function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=x_{1}+\sqrt{x_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 For a given level of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

, the indifference curve for the equation is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}+\sqrt{x_{2}}=\bar{u}\Rightarrow x_{2}=(\bar{u}-x_{1})^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}<\bar{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Draw the indifference curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1}+\epsilon,x_{2})=x_{1}+\epsilon+\sqrt{x_{2}}>x_{1}+\sqrt{x_{2}}=u(x_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset

